One of the two gives the entity, but does not prove the existence of the other3 whilst the latter proves the existence of the former, but does not give it entity (p. 105, l. 1 to p. 106, 1. 9). It does not follow that either is prior to the other, unless in two totally different orders: that of being, and that of cognition (p. 106, l. 9—25). Nor that God’s will, being a mere relation between the Creator and the Created‚ cannot cause anything (l. 26—34).
